    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-02T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-02T12:00:00-05:00" n="125"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d125">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/24641: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-02T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 2, 1942—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 4—4:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1746. Legation’s 1590, September 7.<note n="22" xml:id="d125fn22">Not
                        printed.</note> Letter received today from Smith at Asmara requests that
                    Department be informed that he has returned traveling via the Addis-Asmara Road
                    and resumed charge September 27.</p>
                <p>He stated that he is working on report of his trip and requested that following
                    message be sent to Department.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“It is my understanding that the Emperor of Ethiopia has asked President
                        Roosevelt for permission to join the United Nations Pact.<note n="23"
                            xml:id="d125fn23">See telegram from Emperor Haile Selassie to President
                            Roosevelt, July 28, <ref target="#pg_114">p. 114</ref>.</note> What is
                        the status of this request? The admission of Ethiopia is regarded as
                        conditioned upon a declaration of a state of war between Ethiopia and the
                        Axis Powers. Favorable action would facilitate situation for all parties as
                        otherwise Ethiopia is considered neutral.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>In connection with foregoing see my 1033, June 19, 9 p.m.<note n="24"
                        xml:id="d125fn24">See footnote 17, <ref target="#pg_105">p.
                        105</ref>.</note> and previous.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
